title: For Sale:  Sig Mosqiuto .22LR Reverse Two-Tone
postcontent:
I bought this pistol new in early 2008, in Wichita, KS.  I do not have a round count, but I guess it to be a couple of thousand rounds.

Included is the case, manual, target from factory, spring (for different velocity loads), tool, and two replacement front sights (25yd is on gun, others are for different distances).  All of this comes with the weapon, from the factory.

This weapon was engineered for the CCI Stinger .22LR ammunition.  I have had success with the Blazer (silver box) 40gr ammunition.  If you want to use other ammunition, you may have to switch out the springs, for that velocity.  These are finicky with what ammunition they like to shoot.  As was stated, they were developed using the Stingers and they shoot great with those rounds.  However, those rounds are more expensive than other .22 offerings.  It's still a lot cheaper than 9mm, .40, etc., which is what I bought this pistol for.

I am selling it because I recently had a baby and need money more than I need the pistol, unfortunately.  It has also become a safe queen, since I started reloading.

I vastly prefer a face-to-face sale.  I am willing to drive some, for the right deal, but I do live in Emporia and don't intend to be in Topeka, KC, or Wichita, anytime soon.  If you'd like to test the weapon, you will need to bring your own ammunition, or work out a deal with me (I may be able to provide some, depending on current stock.  I know ammo is still hard to come by.).

postcontent: Never cocked and never fired! Here's a beautiful copy of the Colt Single Action Army revolver that was carried by one of America's most famous military figures, General George S. Patton. This revolver was commissioned by the American Historical Foundation and is based on a Uberti Single Action revolver that has been elaborately hand engraved and silver plated, just like the original. Chambered for the .45 Colt cartridge and wearing a 4-3/4" barrel, this is a fully functional firearm, not just a work of art. The imitation ivory grips have special medallions indicating the years of Patton's birth and passing. The right panel is scrimshawed with the General's initials, just like the original. Condition is perfect with the exception of some slight tarnish to the silver in the protected spots which would easily polish bright if desired. There is no rust, pitting, or handling wear. The revolver was zip-tied at the factory and remains so...never cocked. It comes in a very high quality glass sided display case that allows the gun to be displayed on a shelf or table top and viewed from either side.

title: For Sale:  Front Page Clogger
postcontent:
So someone sends me a message asking if I am an American, if I believe in capitalism and if I believe in American freedoms?  He says if I answer yes to these questions then I should be ok with the guy clogging the front page with his gun ads several times a day.  What?

First, its ok to ask whatever you want when selling anything.  If your asking too much, like the front page clogger, then your stuff just won't sell. 

The problem here is this guy can't sell his junk  because of the high prices, so he posts it several times a day, bumping other ads off the front page.  He is abusing a free site.  Maybe this guy is the New American.  The kind that thinks its ok to take advantage and abuse a free service.  The kind that lays down and takes it, as opposed for standing up for what is right.

How about a little common courtesy?  Is that now Un-American?

title: For Sale/Trade:  1910 SMLE Mk.III Turkish capture
postcontent:
Unfortunately I am needing to sell my 1910 RSAF Enfield made SMLE Mk.III. 

Pics. are here http://imgur.com/a/5gzGP 

It retains all early features: volley-sights, cut-off, windage adjustable rearsight, round cocking piece, and lightening cuts on rearsight protector. The receiver, barrel, forestock, and front sight leaf match. 

The bolt is pre-1915 RSAF Enfield bolt, with a matching numbered cocking piece. The magazine is the only other replacement part I found when I took the entire rifle apart. 

The stock disk indicates that this rifle was issued to the 6th Battalion of the Border Regiment in Feb. of 1915. The Border Regiment was training in France at that time, then left for Gallipoli in late July. This rifle sports a crudely made leather sling, and shows signs of having been on fire near the nosecap. I bought this rifle from a collector a couple years ago, and he bought it from Century about 12 years ago, along with a variety of Turkish Mausers. 

Based off of its condition, the stock disk indicating issue to the Border Regiment in early 1915, the fact that it retains all early features, that the crude sling was sewn on the the rifle, and that it was part of a large group of arms and ammo imported from Turkey, lead me to believe that this rifle was captured by the Turks sometime during the Gallipoli campaign. However, I have no absolute proof of this. 

Asking 450 open to trades for other milsurps

Feel free to call or text me at REDACTED with any questions.

title: For Sale:  Albanian Civil War Sino-Soviet (Tula) SKS
location: Port Allegany, North Central, PA, Pennsylvania
postcontent:
Attention: this is a collectors SKS, not to be confused with the average SKS.

   This is a Russian built Tula SKS that was exported to China in 1955 before the Chinese began their own SKS production. The Chinese then sold these to the Albanian's to arm the freedom fighters in the Albanian Civil War.

   The condition is typical battlefield relic condition with finish wear, dents, scrapes and scratches. the Bore is excellent and the entire unit is 100% functional. there is a chipped of piece of stock (pictured) and does not retain the issued cleaning kit in the butt stock. All numbers match except the receiver cover which was a battlefield repair using a 1956 Chinese cover.

 Remember this is a rare bird, it would greatly decrease the value to modify or alter this SKS. The asking price is $500 or best REASONABLE offer.

title: For Sale/Trade:  -NIB- Stagecoach side by side 20 gauge
postcontent:
Here is a Rossi Overland 20 Gauge Coach Gun. It has 20" barrels, has the original Rossi butt plate, and is unfired and in excellent condition. A slight mark in the butt stock on the right side (see photos) but other than that nothing to report. The breech face and bores show it has not been fired, and the gun is nice and tight. The 20 gauge Rossis are especially nice because the frame of the gun is actually sized for a 20 gauge instead of just having 20 gauge barrels mounted on a 12 gauge frame. This is a really nice gun.

 These Rossi shotguns are great because they are solid and reliable, and there are no extra safeties like the unnecessary tang safety that you find on currently manufactured hammered shotguns.
It is new in box but do not have box. I am 2nd owner and it has been in a show case for 20 years.
